= assigns a value to a variable, while == compares two values.

Using = in a comparison context can cause syntax or logic errors.

In professional code, correct operator choice prevents broken conditions.

Example:
let x = 3;
console.log(x == 3);

== uses type coercion, so it converts '2' into 2 before comparing.

=== compares both value and type, so number 2 and string '2' are different.

In real systems, strict checks prevent accidental matches in validations.

Example:
console.log(2 == '2');
console.log(2 === '2');

With loose equality, false is coerced to 0.

So 0 == false becomes true due to automatic conversion.

Strict equality avoids conversion and keeps logic predictable.

Example:
console.log(0 == false);
console.log(0 === false);

Strict comparison avoids type coercion and compares value with type.

It reduces unexpected behavior and makes debugging simpler.

This is considered clean, professional practice in JavaScript codebases.

Example:
console.log(5 === 5);
console.log(5 === '5');

